!ys-0

# A macro body runs at compile time (macroexpansion), so `reduce`
# computes 10! while the program is compiled. The (fact10) call site
# is replaced by the literal 3628800 in the generated code; nothing
# is multiplied at run time. The macro must precede `main` because
# Clojure macroexpands main's body when it compiles it.
defmacro fact10 []:
  reduce(mul (1 .. 10))

defn main():
  say: "10! = $(fact10())"
